<dl id="n08070j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08070j">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08070j"> 70(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> your grace (to shopkeepers)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">When all the artificialities of the modes of address in different nations are taken into account&mdash;&hellip; the <i>vossa merc&ecirc;</i> (&lsquo;your grace&rsquo;, to shopkeepers) &hellip; of the Portuguese &hellip;, in Swedish &hellip; &lsquo;The gracious Miss is probably aware&rsquo;, etc.)&mdash;the English may be justly proud of having avoided all such mannerisms and ridiculous extravagances <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 233-4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
